[Re: ProMED-mail Toxoplasmosis - Brazil: (PA) 20130629.1799160]
---------------------------------------------------------------
Brazil's obsession with toxoplasmosis is difficult to explain. The term, "toxoplasma" appears in 0.363 percent of all Brazilian publications indexed on PubMed http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed, as compared to 0.086 percent of publications from the United States.

Abstracts from Gideon (http://www.GideonOnline.com) summarize 120 relevant surveys/serosurveys from Brazil, but only 19 from the combined literature of neighboring Bolivia, Argentina, and Venezuela (only 38 from the United States). Strikingly, there have been only 37 Brazilian surveys of HIV infection, and only 9 of dengue as of 2013.

The following list of Brazilian toxoplasma surveys is abstracted from the Gideon e-book series [1,2]. (Primary references available on request)

Prevalence surveys
------------------
- 0.4 percent of solid organ transplant recipients (2001 to 2006)
- 3.8 percent of the general population and 5.8 percent of seropositive individuals in Barra Mansa, Rio de Janeiro State (ocular toxoplasmosis, 2009 publication)
- 19.8 percent of eye diseases treated at an ophthalmology clinic in Sao Paulo (2013 publication)
- 4.8 percent of HIV-positive patients in the southern region (history of neurotoxoplasmosis, 2009 to 2010)
- 10 percent of autopsied AIDS patients (cause of death, Amazonas, 1996 to 2003)
- 7.84 percent of slaughtered goats in Bahia (2009 publication)
- 11.6 percent of horses at slaughter (2013 publication)
- 34 percent and 66 percent of porcine diaphragm and tongue, respectively, in Southern Brazil. (2007 publication)
- 22.58 percent of soil samples from school playgrounds in northwestern Sao Paulo (2010 publication)

