[It is quite understandable that Brazil is concerned about toxoplasmosis, and we disagree that " Brazil's obsession with toxoplasmosis is difficult to explain."

Brazil has a very high burden of ocular toxoplasmosis first described in 1992 (Glasner PD et al: An unusually high prevalence of ocular toxoplasmosis in southern Brazil. Am J Ophthalmol. 1992; 114(2): 136-44; http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1642287. Dubey JP et al: Toxoplasmosis in humans and animals in Brazil: high prevalence, high burden of disease, and epidemiology. Parasitology 2012; 139(11): 1375-424; http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22776427), and congenital toxoplasmosis is more severe in Brazil compared to Europe (Gilbert RE et al: Ocular sequelae of congenital toxoplasmosis in Brazil compared with Europe. PLoS Negl Trop Dis. 2008; 2(8): e277; http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2493041/). The same is found in other countries in South America and is particularly well documented for Colombia and Suriname.

The reason the high burden of _Toxoplasma_-associated posterior uveitis and congenital toxoplasmosis is primarily explained by more virulent genotypes of _Toxoplasma gondii_ (Carneiro AC et al: Genetic characterization of _Toxoplasma gondii_ revealed highly diverse genotypes for isolates from newborns with congenital toxoplasmosis in southeastern Brazil. J Clin Microbiol 2013; 51(3): 901-7; http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23284022) and widespread transmission from contaminated surface water (Bahia-Oliveira LM et al: Highly endemic, waterborne toxoplasmosis in north Rio de Janeiro state, Brazil. Emerg Infect Dis. 2003; 9(1): 55-62; http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2873742/).

Thus, infection with _T. gondii_ is an infection with a much higher morbidity in Brazil compared to Europe and North America, and the prime cause of posterior uveitis. - Mod.EP

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1zJi.]
